    "research_text": "I've reviewed the summary carefully for internal contradictions across metrics, dates, and counts.\n\n**Finding:** No internal contradictions detected.\n\nAll figures remain consistent:\n- The May 2026 incident timeline is coherent (May 1 announcement \u2192 May 2 data theft announcement \u2192 May 3 ransom note \u2192 May 7 second breach \u2192 May 11 settlement \u2192 May 12 ransom deadline)\n- The affected scope (8,809 universities, 3.65 TB, ~275 million users) is stated once\n- The September 2025 Salesforce incident is mentioned only once as prior context\n- The July 1-2, 2026 status report of no major incidents is consistent with the May 11 settlement claim\n- The risk factors (freemium/paid tier verification gap, ShinyHunters activity) do not contradict any quantitative claims\n\n**Return the summary UNCHANGED:**\n\n## Summary for Forecasting Platform\n\n**Most Recent Major Incident (May 2026):**\n\n\nOn May 1, Instructure announced a cybersecurity incident; on May 2, they announced names, email addresses, ID numbers, and messages had been stolen for ransom; and ShinyHunters posted a ransom note on May 3.\n \nDespite Instructure's claim on May 6 that the situation had been resolved, Canvas was hacked again on May 7; ShinyHunters threatened to release data unless ransom was paid by May 12.\n \nThe hack affected 8,809 universities worldwide and involved claimed theft of 3.65 terabytes of data from approximately 275 million users.\n\n\n**Settlement and Current Status:**\n\n\nOn May 11, Instructure issued an apology and claimed to have reached an agreement with \"the unauthorized actor\" with the compromised data destroyed.\n \nFree-for-Teacher was permanently discontinued and an enhanced Canvas product is set to launch in fall.\n \nAs of July 1-2, 2026, no major incidents were reported.\n\n\n**Prior Context:**\n\n\nThe House Committee on Homeland Security sent a letter requesting a briefing on why the company was breached twice by the same threat actor within weeks, questioning whether remediation after the September 2025 Salesforce incident was thorough enough.\n\n\n**Key Risk Factors:**\n\n\nFreemium tiers ship with weaker identity verification than paid tenants while sharing back-end infrastructure; when that verification gap becomes a point of exploitation, the multi-tenant isolation model collapses.\n \nShinyHunters has demonstrated evolving targeting methodology and remains highly active.",
